{% extends "layout.njk" %}
{% set pageTitle = "Khopa | Starplan" %}
{% set description = "Case study for Starplan, a WiFi planning and localization engine." %}
{% set bodyClass = "page-main" %}

{% block mainContent %}
<div class="container project-case">
  <section class="page-hero" data-reveal>
    <p class="eyebrow">Portfolio</p>
    <h1>Starplan</h1>
    <p>WiFi planning, radio heatmaps, and indoor localization tooling.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="project-hero-card" data-reveal>
    <div class="project-summary">
      <p class="eyebrow">WiFi Planning</p>
      <h2>Turning radio behavior into usable planning tools</h2>
      <p>
        Starplan focused on WiFi and radio planning, heatmap generation, and localization features for enterprise environments.
      </p>
      <p>
        Projects like this are interesting because they sit between algorithmic logic, visualization, and practical deployment questions: coverage, positioning, radio realism, and usability for operators.
      </p>
      <ul class="project-facts">
        <li>WiFi</li>
        <li>Heatmaps</li>
        <li>Localization</li>
        <li>Enterprise</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="project-cover">
      <div class="project-cover__media project-cover__media--shot shot shot--forge">
        <span>Radio planning and localization</span>
      </div>
      <p class="project-cover__caption">Coverage analysis, mapping, and device-location workflows for enterprise networking.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="project-panel" data-reveal>
    <p class="eyebrow">Why It Matters</p>
    <h2>Networking software is also a visualization problem</h2>
    <p>
      Beyond backend logic, tools in this space need to communicate technical information clearly: coverage zones, radio behavior, and location signals only become useful when operators can read and trust what they see. And Wifi coverage is not always entirely intuitive.
    </p>
    <div class="project-links">
      <a class="button button--secondary" href="./index.html">Back to portfolio</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</div>
{% endblock %}